00:42:05.660 --> 00:42:08.540
of the government, against
the idea of virtually

00:42:08.540 --> 00:42:10.640
having a government.

00:42:10.640 --> 00:42:11.760
Government is the problem.

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:12.530
Government is the enemy.

00:42:12.530 --> 00:42:13.779
The government is taking this.

00:42:13.779 --> 00:42:15.200
The government is doing that.

00:42:15.200 --> 00:42:17.570
Now, I think most people
here probably don't subscribe

00:42:17.570 --> 00:42:18.820
to that version of the theory.

00:42:21.580 --> 00:42:25.270
That has been a very
successful revolution.

00:42:25.270 --> 00:42:28.840
Government has
truly scaled back.

00:42:28.840 --> 00:42:31.090
There's a reason that that
private philanthropy giving

00:42:31.090 --> 00:42:37.450
is starting to approach the
level of federal nonmilitary

00:42:37.450 --> 00:42:40.390
spending--
discretionary spending.

00:42:40.390 --> 00:42:43.240
But one of the things
that I explore in the book

00:42:43.240 --> 00:42:45.250
is that that
revolution prosecuted

00:42:45.250 --> 00:42:47.440
by the political right
didn't end there,

00:42:47.440 --> 00:42:50.740
because often what happens when
a revolution like that succeeds

00:42:50.740 --> 00:42:53.350
is that it kind of changes the
cultural atmosphere in which

00:42:53.350 --> 00:42:54.710
everybody operates.

00:42:54.710 --> 00:42:57.340
And even those on
the other side of it

00:42:57.340 --> 00:43:01.960
end up playing on its
field, if you see it I mean.

00:43:01.960 --> 00:43:05.355
You may be an
opponent of that idea,

00:43:05.355 --> 00:43:06.730
but you're not
playing that game.

00:43:06.730 --> 00:43:08.410
You're forced to play that game.

00:43:08.410 --> 00:43:12.520
So it is not an accident
that, after Reagan said

00:43:12.520 --> 00:43:15.310
government is the
problem, some years

00:43:15.310 --> 00:43:17.650
later, Bill Clinton
from the other party--

00:43:17.650 --> 00:43:20.750
very different world view,
much more favorable view

00:43:20.750 --> 00:43:23.380
of government-- nonetheless
said the era of big government

00:43:23.380 --> 00:43:25.480
is over.

00:43:25.480 --> 00:43:29.140
That's what it means
to be an opponent who's

00:43:29.140 --> 00:43:32.800
still fundamentally playing
on someone else's field.

00:43:32.800 --> 00:43:37.717
And I fully, fully, fully agree
with you that one of the most

00:43:37.717 --> 00:43:40.300
essential things we need to do--
and I end the book by talking

00:43:40.300 --> 00:43:42.280
about this on a hopeful note--

00:43:42.280 --> 00:43:45.640
is we need to redeem the idea
of government in people's eyes.

00:43:45.640 --> 00:43:48.964
Is the government bloated, and
inefficient, and underfunded,

00:43:48.964 --> 00:43:50.380
and not good at a
bunch of things?

00:43:50.380 --> 00:43:55.030
Yeah, but as you say, the
government is also a miracle.

00:43:55.030 --> 00:43:56.280
All the things that go right--

00:43:56.280 --> 00:43:58.030
I mean, have you been
to other countries

00:43:58.030 --> 00:44:01.840
where you need to
do a lot of homework

00:44:01.840 --> 00:44:03.145
before you eat out in public?

00:44:05.079 --> 00:44:07.495
When was the last time you got
sick eating in a restaurant

00:44:07.495 --> 00:44:08.455
in America.

00:44:08.455 --> 00:44:11.080
When was the last time you
put your kid in a car seat

00:44:11.080 --> 00:44:13.750
and wondered if it had
been properly tested?

00:44:13.750 --> 00:44:17.740
When was the last time
you stayed in a hotel room

00:44:17.740 --> 00:44:21.280
and wondered if it was safe
or it had been cleaned?

00:44:24.050 --> 00:44:26.710
I mean, you think
about all the greed

00:44:26.710 --> 00:44:29.650
in this society-- even
Wall Street, for all that

00:44:29.650 --> 00:44:33.310
it does wrong, it is so
carefully regulated and hyper

00:44:33.310 --> 00:44:36.287
regulated, and you can't
just do crazy stuff,

00:44:36.287 --> 00:44:37.870
except every now and
then when you can

00:44:37.870 --> 00:44:40.520
and tank the world economy.

00:44:40.520 --> 00:44:42.950
But we forget how
much works right

00:44:42.950 --> 00:44:47.200
because we have not
some big overbearing

00:44:47.200 --> 00:44:49.390
evil step-dad of a
government, but because we

00:44:49.390 --> 00:44:53.290
have a government that actually
in all these million unsung

00:44:53.290 --> 00:44:55.072
ways tends to common welfare.

00:44:55.072 --> 00:44:55.780
And I would say--

00:44:55.780 --> 00:44:57.238
I'm not saying
Google specifically,

00:44:57.238 --> 00:44:59.980
but Silicon Valley
institutions and the complex

00:44:59.980 --> 00:45:04.730
of thinking around tech
have been part, I think,

00:45:04.730 --> 00:45:08.710
of discrediting government,
of framing government

00:45:08.710 --> 00:45:15.400
as this old kind of 1.0 thing
that can't really fix things

00:45:15.400 --> 00:45:20.170
anymore, and crediting the
kind of innovative sphere

00:45:20.170 --> 00:45:22.630
as being the place where
real change happens.

00:45:22.630 --> 00:45:25.031
And I think that's very
unfortunate, not least

00:45:25.031 --> 00:45:26.530
because the entire
internet was made

00:45:26.530 --> 00:45:30.790
by the government in its
origin, but also because there's

00:45:30.790 --> 00:45:33.070
a real reason that
Silicon Valley didn't

00:45:33.070 --> 00:45:35.860
arise in another country.

00:45:35.860 --> 00:45:37.750
A lot of the common
institutions we

00:45:37.750 --> 00:45:41.770
share in this country-- the
courts, the boring stuff

00:45:41.770 --> 00:45:44.900
that you don't even realize
allows you to do what you do

00:45:44.900 --> 00:45:46.590
are public things,
are common things,

00:45:46.590 --> 00:45:47.770
are things we share
in common, and we

00:45:47.770 --> 00:45:49.420
need to give those
things more credit.

00:45:49.420 --> 00:45:52.240
Otherwise we're going to head
into a society that is actually

00:45:52.240 --> 00:45:54.370
like many very poor
countries where there's

00:45:54.370 --> 00:45:56.290
a lot of rich people and
some great companies,

00:45:56.290 --> 00:45:59.560
and most people are just
not part of the economy,

00:45:59.560 --> 00:46:01.725
are not part of
building a better world,

00:46:01.725 --> 00:46:03.433
and I don't think
that's actually a world

00:46:03.433 --> 00:46:05.010
that anybody wants to live in.

00:46:05.010 --> 00:46:06.010
AUDIENCE: So in your
discussion today,

00:46:06.010 --> 00:46:07.884
you've talked about some
of the problems that

00:46:07.884 --> 00:46:10.110
can result from good
faith actors who

00:46:10.110 --> 00:46:13.241
maybe go about things in a way
that's not helpful to society.

00:46:13.241 --> 00:46:14.740
How much of the
problem do you think

00:46:14.740 --> 00:46:16.370
comes from bad faith actors?

00:46:16.370 --> 00:46:19.600
Or how much do they end
up co-opting or corrupting

00:46:19.600 --> 00:46:21.010
good faith efforts?

00:46:21.010 --> 00:46:23.000
ANAND GIRIDHARADAS:
That's a great question.

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:27.460
I mean, I focused
this book on people

00:46:27.460 --> 00:46:31.734
who I think are genuine in
trying to make a difference

00:46:31.734 --> 00:46:33.400
and who end up upholding
the system that

00:46:33.400 --> 00:46:36.452
causes the problems, but
you're exactly right.

00:46:36.452 --> 00:46:38.160
And I think that has
more to do with what

00:46:38.160 --> 00:46:40.080
I saying a moment ago.

00:46:40.080 --> 00:46:43.600
When I think about
the Koch brothers,

00:46:43.600 --> 00:46:46.120
they're not part of my story.

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:50.290
When I think about Fox News,
that's not part of my story.

00:46:50.290 --> 00:46:54.340
I don't think that those
are people chiefly motivated

00:46:54.340 --> 00:46:56.212
by making the world
a better place.

00:46:56.212 --> 00:46:57.670
I think those are
people who wanted

00:46:57.670 --> 00:47:00.370
to grab wealth and
power, and understood

00:47:00.370 --> 00:47:04.660
that a certain kind of influence
campaign and changing people's

00:47:04.660 --> 00:47:08.890
norms and values, and
kind of tricking--

00:47:08.890 --> 00:47:11.680
astroturfing issues
so that regular people

00:47:11.680 --> 00:47:15.060
supported things that actually
only benefit billionaires--

00:47:15.060 --> 00:47:20.170
that that was a cynical effort
to achieve their own business

00:47:20.170 --> 00:47:23.050
interest at the
expense of the society.

00:47:23.050 --> 00:47:25.000
And there's a very
good book on that

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:27.770
called "Dark Money" by Jane
Mayer about how that was done.

00:47:27.770 --> 00:47:29.020
That's not my story.

00:47:29.020 --> 00:47:34.630
My story is the story of how
is it that Mark Zuckerberg can

00:47:34.630 --> 00:47:40.610
be one of the most powerful
idealists in American history,

00:47:40.610 --> 00:47:43.090
but also the first person
in American history

00:47:43.090 --> 00:47:49.030
to potentially allow an
election to be compromised.

00:47:49.030 --> 00:47:50.980
And are those things
just a coincidence,

00:47:50.980 --> 00:47:55.550
or is his idealism
part of why he

00:47:55.550 --> 00:47:59.620
was able to get enough power
to have the election be

00:47:59.620 --> 00:48:04.156
compromised, and part of why,
when reporter friends of mine

00:48:04.156 --> 00:48:05.780
have tried to
investigate what happened

00:48:05.780 --> 00:48:07.070
and what happened with
Cambridge Analytica,

00:48:07.070 --> 00:48:09.470
they get so much pushback
from him and his company

00:48:09.470 --> 00:48:11.290
that they can
barely do their job?

00:48:11.290 --> 00:48:14.750
Is his idealism and his
sense of himself as a savior

00:48:14.750 --> 00:48:18.860
part of what actually
allows that problem

00:48:18.860 --> 00:48:20.730
to happen the way it did?

00:48:20.730 --> 00:48:22.530
AUDIENCE: So you
asked the question,

00:48:22.530 --> 00:48:24.740
what are we already doing?

00:48:24.740 --> 00:48:27.050
And one answer
that comes to mind

00:48:27.050 --> 00:48:29.840
that I see at
Google and elsewhere

00:48:29.840 --> 00:48:32.120
is the issue of subcontracting.

00:48:32.120 --> 00:48:34.490
There' was a great "New
York Times" article recently

00:48:34.490 --> 00:48:38.165
comparing a janitor at Kodak I
think in the '70s and a janitor

00:48:38.165 --> 00:48:41.900
at Apple today, and back in
the day, the janitor at Kodak

00:48:41.900 --> 00:48:44.930
received the same vacation
and health benefits

00:48:44.930 --> 00:48:46.520
as every other Kodak employee.

00:48:46.520 --> 00:48:51.410
And now the janitor at Apple is
an employee of some contracting

00:48:51.410 --> 00:48:53.450
company, and they're
not receiving

00:48:53.450 --> 00:48:57.110
any of the same benefits,
and my understanding is

00:48:57.110 --> 00:49:00.890
the situation is similar here.

00:49:00.890 --> 00:49:04.580
And we see these
workers every day.

00:49:04.580 --> 00:49:08.377
Can you comment at all on
that particular situation?

00:49:08.377 --> 00:49:10.210
ANAND GIRIDHARADAS:
That's a great question.

00:49:10.210 --> 00:49:11.960
There's another story
even more recently.

00:49:11.960 --> 00:49:13.830
The Kodak one was amazing.

00:49:13.830 --> 00:49:18.170
There's another story a couple
of days ago about Harvard,

00:49:18.170 --> 00:49:22.640
and the students at Harvard
on the exact same issue

00:49:22.640 --> 00:49:25.730
you named revolted
against the administration

00:49:25.730 --> 00:49:27.650
and basically
forced them to stop

00:49:27.650 --> 00:49:31.820
doing this thing of
subcontracting it out to--

00:49:31.820 --> 00:49:35.130
essentially it's like the labor
version of shell companies

00:49:35.130 --> 00:49:37.309
so that you can say
I had no idea they

00:49:37.309 --> 00:49:38.600
didn't provide maternity leave.

00:49:38.600 --> 00:49:39.160
I'm shocked.

00:49:39.160 --> 00:49:41.420
Shocked.

00:49:41.420 --> 00:49:43.630
And Harvard students
found out about that

00:49:43.630 --> 00:49:46.430
and pushed Larry Summers, who
was the president of Harvard

00:49:46.430 --> 00:49:51.620
at the time, and
Harvard fixed it.

00:49:51.620 --> 00:49:57.170
And the story was focused
on this woman who works--

00:49:57.170 --> 00:49:59.890
I forget what part of the
university she works in--

00:49:59.890 --> 00:50:02.000
but she and her
husband between them

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:06.200
make a low six figure income
both doing working class jobs.

00:50:06.200 --> 00:50:10.524
It's exactly like what it used
to be at Kodak in the past,

00:50:10.524 --> 00:50:11.690
and they make a good living.

00:50:11.690 --> 00:50:12.530
They have a home.

00:50:12.530 --> 00:50:15.080
They are living in
dignity and decency,

00:50:15.080 --> 00:50:21.170
and it was because students
said don't clean up after us,

00:50:21.170 --> 00:50:24.520
or don't serve us food in a way
that's degrading other people.

00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:27.020
And so look, one of the things
that people have talked about

00:50:27.020 --> 00:50:30.050
is, relative to most
employees in America,

00:50:30.050 --> 00:50:32.120
you have a lot of power.

00:50:32.120 --> 00:50:34.184
You really do.

00:50:34.184 --> 00:50:36.350
The China thing, the Microsoft
thing that happened--

00:50:36.350 --> 00:50:38.140
these are all stories--

00:50:38.140 --> 00:50:40.280
particularly the people
with that kind of coding

00:50:40.280 --> 00:50:43.040
and engineering background
have an enormous amount

00:50:43.040 --> 00:50:46.190
of power in these companies,
but you all have a lot of power.

00:50:46.190 --> 00:50:47.750
You're very talented
people, and each

00:50:47.750 --> 00:50:49.795
of you in general with
a couple exceptions--

00:50:49.795 --> 00:50:51.920
there's always a couple
exceptions, but each of you

00:50:51.920 --> 00:50:56.200
generally would be a huge
loss for your company.

00:50:56.200 --> 00:51:00.269
They don't want your talent next
door fighting for someone else.

00:51:00.269 --> 00:51:02.060
And then I think you've
got to think about,

00:51:02.060 --> 00:51:03.750
who do you use that?

00:51:03.750 --> 00:51:05.810
If there were people
at this company who

00:51:05.810 --> 00:51:09.950
wanted to work on
that issue, I 100%

00:51:09.950 --> 00:51:12.950
guarantee you you could get
that issue done in a month,

00:51:12.950 --> 00:51:16.520
and that would
have a huge effect.

00:51:16.520 --> 00:51:19.880
How many offices does Google
have around the world?

00:51:19.880 --> 00:51:21.180
AUDIENCE: A lot.

00:51:21.180 --> 00:51:24.200
ANAND GIRIDHARADAS: That
would have a huge, real effect

00:51:24.200 --> 00:51:27.350
this month on a lot of people's
lives, on people's kids,

00:51:27.350 --> 00:51:30.450
and whether their kids
can go to school or not--

00:51:30.450 --> 00:51:31.670
real.

00:51:31.670 --> 00:51:35.060
That's an example of using
that power in a way that

00:51:35.060 --> 00:51:40.010
feels right, but that involves
a painful conversation

00:51:40.010 --> 00:51:42.620
about that's going
to cost real money.

00:51:42.620 --> 00:51:45.920
That's going to come at
the expense of something,

00:51:45.920 --> 00:51:48.800
and those are exactly
the kind of conversations

00:51:48.800 --> 00:51:51.050
I would encourage you to have.

00:51:51.050 --> 00:51:53.650
And I think one of the myths--

00:51:53.650 --> 00:51:56.496
one of the people that read the
book recently and explore kind

00:51:56.496 --> 00:51:58.370
of what it meant for
her-- she said this very

00:51:58.370 --> 00:52:02.390
profound thing,
which is this book

00:52:02.390 --> 00:52:08.270
has made me resist my urge
to overestimate the risks

00:52:08.270 --> 00:52:10.590
of speaking truth to power.

00:52:10.590 --> 00:52:12.680
I think we all tend to
overestimate the risk

00:52:12.680 --> 00:52:14.162
of speaking truth to power.

00:52:14.162 --> 00:52:16.370
I actually think if you
raised the issue you raised--

00:52:16.370 --> 00:52:20.690
I don't think anything
would happen to you,

00:52:20.690 --> 00:52:22.956
and we could all do
more on those fronts.

00:52:22.956 --> 00:52:24.830
So thank you for your
question, and good luck

00:52:24.830 --> 00:52:25.790
with your campaign.

00:52:25.790 --> 00:52:27.087
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:27.087 --> 00:52:29.045
AUDIENCE: Looking forward
to reading your book,

00:52:29.045 --> 00:52:32.540
and thank you for,
in your words,

00:52:32.540 --> 00:52:35.570
coming and speaking in
the belly of the beast.

00:52:35.570 --> 00:52:40.520
My question is regarding
global movement of capital.

00:52:40.520 --> 00:52:43.550
I mean, capital moves
with complete impunity,

00:52:43.550 --> 00:52:46.390
and the issues that
you spoke about--

00:52:46.390 --> 00:52:51.120
health care, education-- all
of these are national issues.

00:52:51.120 --> 00:52:53.460
How, without any
democratic control

00:52:53.460 --> 00:52:59.260
over movement of capital
versus, say, movement of labor--

00:52:59.260 --> 00:53:01.620
how are we going to make
any real effective changes

00:53:01.620 --> 00:53:02.790
and what--

00:53:02.790 --> 00:53:04.630
of course, this is a
very general question,

00:53:04.630 --> 00:53:09.210
but what do you think
we, as Google employees,

00:53:09.210 --> 00:53:10.987
can even say or do
about some of these?

00:53:10.987 --> 00:53:12.820
ANAND GIRIDHARADAS:
That's a great question.

00:53:12.820 --> 00:53:16.835
I mean, so when I think about,
if you're persuaded by me,

00:53:16.835 --> 00:53:18.960
that we need to do less of
the fake change and more

00:53:18.960 --> 00:53:19.477
real change.

00:53:19.477 --> 00:53:21.810
You start thinking about, OK,
what are the three or four

00:53:21.810 --> 00:53:26.060
really big areas of
American life where

00:53:26.060 --> 00:53:28.560
a little tinkering is
not going to solve it,

00:53:28.560 --> 00:53:32.730
where are we need some
transformational reform?

00:53:32.730 --> 00:53:33.760
I would say a couple.

00:53:33.760 --> 00:53:35.700
One is health.

00:53:35.700 --> 00:53:38.310
Regardless of what your
view is on the right system,

00:53:38.310 --> 00:53:39.830
I think we can all
agree we're not

00:53:39.830 --> 00:53:42.660
a particularly healthy country.

00:53:42.660 --> 00:53:43.452
It's very cruel.

00:53:43.452 --> 00:53:45.660
People are dying of things
they don't need to die of.

00:53:45.660 --> 00:53:46.980
Life expectancy is going down.

00:53:46.980 --> 00:53:48.854
It's not supposed to
move in that direction--

00:53:48.854 --> 00:53:49.992
health.

00:53:49.992 --> 00:53:51.450
I think we'd all
agree on education

00:53:51.450 --> 00:53:54.580
as another major area, major
transformational change

00:53:54.580 --> 00:53:57.300
required simply to keep up
with where the world is.

00:53:57.300 --> 00:54:00.390
I think a third area is
labor and thinking about work

00:54:00.390 --> 00:54:03.270
and the kind of
question that was raised

00:54:03.270 --> 00:54:05.630
by that woman,
but also questions

00:54:05.630 --> 00:54:08.550
around what does it
mean to protect an Uber

00:54:08.550 --> 00:54:11.750
driver from the vicissitudes
of the gig economy?

00:54:11.750 --> 00:54:15.000
And the solutions
we have don't really

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:17.792
fit the realities we've created,
but the fourth area that I

00:54:17.792 --> 00:54:19.500
think is a big one is
the one you raised,

00:54:19.500 --> 00:54:26.460
which is, in a world where
money is not necessarily

00:54:26.460 --> 00:54:28.850
a physical thing in your
wallet, not just a thing

00:54:28.850 --> 00:54:30.960
in an account anymore
either, but can be--

00:54:30.960 --> 00:54:33.293
I mean, I don't understand
what all of these things are,

00:54:33.293 --> 00:54:35.490
but you probably
do, but is virtual,

00:54:35.490 --> 00:54:38.050
and can bounce around untraced,
and can be anonymized,

00:54:38.050 --> 00:54:40.410
and can be moved
through shell companies,

00:54:40.410 --> 00:54:43.500
and transferred, and
turned into things faster

00:54:43.500 --> 00:54:49.107
than any government may ever
be able to make sense of.

00:54:49.107 --> 00:54:50.440
What does it mean to tax people?

00:54:53.850 --> 00:54:55.710
Let's just face reality.

00:54:55.710 --> 00:54:58.980
Many of the largest
American corporations

00:54:58.980 --> 00:55:02.790
do not pay corporate income
tax in any given year.

00:55:02.790 --> 00:55:05.880
I'm talking about big,
big, big, big companies--

00:55:05.880 --> 00:55:09.630
companies that make an
enormous amount of money.

00:55:09.630 --> 00:55:11.650
There's the double Dutch
with an Irish sandwich.

00:55:11.650 --> 00:55:13.066
I don't know if
you've eaten that,

00:55:13.066 --> 00:55:15.807
but that's a tax
maneuver that saves--

00:55:15.807 --> 00:55:18.140
a lot of companies pretend
to be a lot bigger in Ireland

00:55:18.140 --> 00:55:18.990
than they actually are.

00:55:18.990 --> 00:55:19.906
Let's put it that way.

00:55:22.590 --> 00:55:26.080
You've got all these tax havens
that kind of rich individuals

00:55:26.080 --> 00:55:28.110
use-- and others.

00:55:28.110 --> 00:55:29.850
And I think we just
have to face I don't

00:55:29.850 --> 00:55:32.490
know what the answer
is, but in a world

00:55:32.490 --> 00:55:34.107
in which it is as
easy as it is--

00:55:34.107 --> 00:55:35.940
and by the way, all of
that that I described

00:55:35.940 --> 00:55:37.620
is without any of
this crypto stuff

00:55:37.620 --> 00:55:39.450
having really affected it.

00:55:39.450 --> 00:55:41.670
We haven't even seen--

00:55:41.670 --> 00:55:44.950
when GE adopts crypto.

00:55:44.950 --> 00:55:46.170
It's going to be a slow--

00:55:46.170 --> 00:55:49.110
and then that becomes part of
how we have figure out taxing,

00:55:49.110 --> 00:55:51.520
it's going to be a nightmare.

00:55:51.520 --> 00:55:53.230
And we're very-- if
we're not careful,

00:55:53.230 --> 00:55:57.600
we are heading into a world in
which the most important pots

00:55:57.600 --> 00:56:03.360
of money to tax to fund
a basic common existence

00:56:03.360 --> 00:56:06.275
are going to be invisible
to the taxation authorities.

00:56:06.275 --> 00:56:07.650
And so what can
you at Google do?

00:56:07.650 --> 00:56:11.040
I mean, the technology
and know how you have--

00:56:11.040 --> 00:56:13.290
you're probably one of the
few people who can actually

00:56:13.290 --> 00:56:15.460
think about solving that issue.

00:56:15.460 --> 00:56:19.330
From the beginning of this money
revolution that's happening,

00:56:19.330 --> 00:56:26.190
how do we embed in
those inventions

00:56:26.190 --> 00:56:30.475
the ability to tax people?

00:56:30.475 --> 00:56:35.307
That's antithetical to why a
lot of these people do crypto,

00:56:35.307 --> 00:56:37.390
but one of the things we
learned with the internet

00:56:37.390 --> 00:56:42.210
that you know very well is early
design choices matter a lot.

00:56:42.210 --> 00:56:46.230
The internet was designed
to protect anonymity,

00:56:46.230 --> 00:56:48.890
and that's very hard
to work around that.

00:56:48.890 --> 00:56:53.400
Well, the internet ended up
being this incredibly abusive,

00:56:53.400 --> 00:56:58.500
racist space, and if
persistent identity

00:56:58.500 --> 00:57:01.920
had been more of a part of the
early design of the internet,

00:57:01.920 --> 00:57:04.009
maybe the internet would
be in a different way.

00:57:04.009 --> 00:57:05.550
Maybe people would
behave online more

00:57:05.550 --> 00:57:08.370
than the way they do at cocktail
parties, which is occasionally

00:57:08.370 --> 00:57:11.490
mean, but not calling
people by racist names

00:57:11.490 --> 00:57:15.100
every time they say something
that slightly offends them.

00:57:15.100 --> 00:57:16.600
These kind of design
choices matter,

00:57:16.600 --> 00:57:18.141
so I think it's
worth thinking about,

00:57:18.141 --> 00:57:21.890
how do you design money, this
new money in a way that is not

00:57:21.890 --> 00:57:23.640
going to lead to a
world in which there is

00:57:23.640 --> 00:57:26.140
no money for the common good?

