00:58:18.825 --> 00:58:20.700
ANAND GIRIDHARADAS:
That's an important asset

00:58:20.700 --> 00:58:22.800
in making change.

00:58:22.800 --> 00:58:25.200
AUDIENCE: I got
surprisingly little pushback

00:58:25.200 --> 00:58:26.670
as it went up the chain--

00:58:26.670 --> 00:58:33.379
only just crisp up your
message, but go for it.

00:58:33.379 --> 00:58:34.920
The only thing I
want to push back on

00:58:34.920 --> 00:58:39.480
is it's not always easy
to tell when you're

00:58:39.480 --> 00:58:40.860
being the Goliath or not.

00:58:40.860 --> 00:58:43.480
So Google started off
as a very small company.

00:58:43.480 --> 00:58:43.980
We grew.

00:58:43.980 --> 00:58:47.130
We put a lot of businesses
out of business.

00:58:47.130 --> 00:58:48.720
Was that bad?

00:58:48.720 --> 00:58:52.550
Which of those businesses that
we put out of business was bad?

00:58:52.550 --> 00:58:55.170
There's some, I think, fairly
relatively clear cut cases,

00:58:55.170 --> 00:58:57.625
but with a lot of
cases companies

00:58:57.625 --> 00:59:00.000
grow, and then they get old,
and they become inefficient,

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:01.625
and they eventually
go out of business.

00:59:01.625 --> 00:59:06.220
Google will not be in business
probably 300 years from now.

00:59:06.220 --> 00:59:08.270
That's OK.

00:59:08.270 --> 00:59:09.970
What are your
guidelines for that?

00:59:09.970 --> 00:59:12.511
ANAND GIRIDHARADAS: I think the
simple answer for that that's

00:59:12.511 --> 00:59:14.520
actually embedded in the law--

00:59:14.520 --> 00:59:17.130
it is not bad to put another
company out of business

00:59:17.130 --> 00:59:20.090
when you do so out of an
abundance of competition.

00:59:20.090 --> 00:59:21.684
It is bad to put
another company out

00:59:21.684 --> 00:59:23.100
of business when
you do so because

00:59:23.100 --> 00:59:24.722
of a lack of competition.

00:59:24.722 --> 00:59:26.180
So when you guys
were starting out,

00:59:26.180 --> 00:59:30.720
and you were smarter and
nimbler than competitors,

00:59:30.720 --> 00:59:32.530
and there were a
bunch of competitors,

00:59:32.530 --> 00:59:35.370
and people wanted to come
to you instead of them,

00:59:35.370 --> 00:59:37.470
I don't think anybody
cries for that,

00:59:37.470 --> 00:59:41.280
except the people who are being
disrupted, as you guys say.

00:59:41.280 --> 00:59:43.230
But I think when
you get to a state

00:59:43.230 --> 00:59:45.390
where there's many
people wanting

00:59:45.390 --> 00:59:49.440
to advertise basically only one
company left to do their ad buy

00:59:49.440 --> 00:59:55.080
on, and you then see "The New
York Times," or "The Washington

00:59:55.080 --> 00:59:58.380
Post," or actually, more to
the point, smaller newspapers

00:59:58.380 --> 01:00:01.830
struggling to exist--

01:00:01.830 --> 01:00:08.130
at that point, I don't think
that business is struggling

01:00:08.130 --> 01:00:12.420
because only of competition.

01:00:12.420 --> 01:00:15.810
I think if there were eight
Googles vying for the online ad

01:00:15.810 --> 01:00:19.650
business the price
dynamics in the market

01:00:19.650 --> 01:00:23.710
might be different enough that
that newspaper could compete.

01:00:23.710 --> 01:00:25.371
So I think you have
to ask yourself,

01:00:25.371 --> 01:00:27.120
when is there an
abundance of competition,

01:00:27.120 --> 01:00:31.170
and when have we become
the thing that results

01:00:31.170 --> 01:00:32.640
in a lack of competition?

01:00:32.640 --> 01:00:33.360
